@Implementation:
emit_left_brace.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_script_block_start" takes emitter as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Emit start of PowerShell script block {}

    proc emit_left_brace with emitter

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Emits `}` closing the script block opened by emit_script_block_start.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
emit_right_brace.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_script_block_end" takes emitter as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Emit end of PowerShell script block

    proc emit_right_brace with emitter

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Emits `-ParameterName` — a named PowerShell parameter passed to a
cmdlet.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
emit_hyphen then emit_string of the parameter name.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_parameter" takes emitter as Integer, name as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Emit PowerShell parameter (-ParameterName)

    proc emit_hyphen with emitter
    proc emit_string with emitter, name

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Emits `$varname` — a PowerShell variable reference.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
emit_dollar then emit_string of the variable name.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_variable" takes emitter as Integer, name as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Emit PowerShell variable ($variableName)

    proc emit_dollar with emitter
    proc emit_string with emitter, name

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Emits ` | ` — pipeline separator with surrounding spaces matching
PowerShell formatting conventions.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
emit_space, emit_pipe, emit_space in sequence.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_pipeline_separator" takes emitter as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Emit pipeline separator with proper spacing

    proc emit_space with emitter
    proc emit_pipe with emitter
    proc emit_space with emitter

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Emits ` = ` — assignment operator with surrounding spaces.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
emit_space, emit_equals, emit_space in sequence.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_assignment_operator" takes emitter as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Emit assignment operator with proper spacing

    proc emit_space with emitter
    proc emit_equals with emitter
    proc emit_space with emitter

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Output Retrieval
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Returns the assembled PowerShell source string. The output is
NUL-terminated and owned by the emitter; callers must not free.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Delegates to emitter_raw_get_output from EmitterCommon which
NUL-terminates the buffer and returns its pointer.
@End Implementation

Process called "get_output" takes emitter as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc emitter_raw_get_output from EmitterCommon with emitter
End Process

@Reasoning:
Returns the current byte length of emitted output. Used by callers
who want to track size or reserve buffers downstream.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Delegates to emitter_raw_length from EmitterCommon which returns
the length field directly.
@End Implementation

Process called "get_length" takes emitter as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc emitter_raw_length from EmitterCommon with emitter
End Process

@Reasoning:
Clears the buffer to empty without releasing the allocation. Used
when reusing the emitter for multiple successive emissions.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Delegates to emitter_raw_reset from EmitterCommon which sets length
to 0 (keeping capacity intact for amortised reuse).
@End Implementation

Process called "reset" takes emitter as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc emitter_raw_reset from EmitterCommon with emitter
End Process

Note: End of PowerShell Emitter